1
00:00:05,661 --> 00:00:07,276
<i>Previously on</i> Mad Men.

2
00:00:07,597 --> 00:00:09,918
You have any idea how unhappy
I was before I met you.

3
00:00:10,071 --> 00:00:11,621
I was thinking of leaving my wife.

4
00:00:11,785 --> 00:00:13,593
They call a girl like her a lobster,

5
00:00:13,785 --> 00:00:14,903
all the meat's in the tail.

6
00:00:19,024 --> 00:00:22,393
If it is kennedy, nixon will lower
himself to the occasion.

7
00:00:22,624 --> 00:00:23,961
It's going to be kennedy.

8
00:00:24,298 --> 00:00:27,739
My mother used to say,
"you're going to get stout."

9
00:00:28,200 --> 00:00:29,217
Tell me more about that.

10
00:00:29,801 --> 00:00:30,801
I miss her.

11
00:00:31,243 --> 00:00:32,969
I'm living like there's no tomorrow,

12
00:00:33,455 --> 00:00:35,078
because there isn't one.

13
00:01:12,160 --> 00:01:14,225
Season 1 Episode 10
<i>Long Weekend</i>

14
00:01:16,539 --> 00:01:17,959
Running in the house.

15
00:01:18,245 --> 00:01:20,452
Grandpa's here, and his aunt Gloria.

16
00:01:22,988 --> 00:01:25,536
If I leave, can you keep
your mouth shut?

18
00:01:35,181 --> 00:01:37,760
Elizabeth, are you hiding
your sugar bowl from me?

20
00:01:38,268 --> 00:01:40,638
Gene, I think I have some packets
from the Howard Johnson.

21
00:01:42,254 --> 00:01:44,744
Daddy, have a saccharin or nothing.

22
00:01:45,778 --> 00:01:47,436
Where is your sugar bowl?

23
00:01:47,696 --> 00:01:50,105
Do you want to wake up with
a cold leg like grandpa herman?

24
00:01:51,163 --> 00:01:53,692
Diabetics don't live long, and
sometimes they lose their legs.

25
00:01:56,541 --> 00:01:57,738
Hey grandpa.

26
00:01:57,923 --> 00:01:58,739
Good morning.

27
00:02:00,351 --> 00:02:02,352
- Good to see you, Gene.
- Don.

28
00:02:04,067 --> 00:02:05,664
This is my friend Gloria.

29
00:02:05,868 --> 00:02:07,324
I heard you might be joining us.

30
00:02:07,514 --> 00:02:09,124
It's good to have another
woman around.

31
00:02:09,277 --> 00:02:10,417
Give betty a break.

32
00:02:10,683 --> 00:02:11,938
I live to serve.

33
00:02:12,161 --> 00:02:13,453
Hey, you heard that, right?

34
00:02:13,852 --> 00:02:15,005
I have a witness.

35
00:02:16,029 --> 00:02:17,716
She's a hell of a sport.

36
00:02:18,126 --> 00:02:20,193
Don, will you help me
with the suitcase?

37
00:02:20,509 --> 00:02:22,388
We're only going for the weekend.

38
00:02:22,641 --> 00:02:24,719
I can't get it out of the closet.

39
00:02:26,527 --> 00:02:28,229
Honestly, it's unseemly.

40
00:02:28,531 --> 00:02:30,081
I can imagine everyone at the club.

41
00:02:30,388 --> 00:02:31,750
Was she waiting at the funeral,

42
00:02:31,902 --> 00:02:34,525
unbuttoning her top button like
at some sadie hawkins dance?

43
00:02:34,785 --> 00:02:36,935
She seems like a perfectly nice lady.

44
00:02:38,733 --> 00:02:40,908
What am I supposed to do with this?
Fill it with hay?

45
00:02:41,046 --> 00:02:42,493
How far do you want to go with this?

46
00:02:42,810 --> 00:02:44,418
Oh, I'll say you talked me out of it.

47
00:02:44,721 --> 00:02:46,000
She's a vulture.

48
00:02:47,164 --> 00:02:48,846
Her husband was a failure.

49
00:02:49,665 --> 00:02:52,988
When he died they found out
he cheated on his income taxes.

50
00:02:53,318 --> 00:02:55,080
And her kids, louise never married.

51
00:02:55,247 --> 00:02:58,300
Two more years and she'll be hanging
out at funerals too.

52
00:02:59,102 --> 00:03:01,394
Huntley, he was my brother's age.

53
00:03:01,523 --> 00:03:03,220
- He was always funny.
- Birdy,

54
00:03:04,456 --> 00:03:06,593
your father was married
what, 40 years?

55
00:03:07,040 --> 00:03:10,087
The man can hardly fix himself
a cup of tea, let alone do laundry.

56
00:03:10,445 --> 00:03:12,136
All he needs is a housekeeper.

57
00:03:12,339 --> 00:03:13,689
A housekeeper goes home at night.

58
00:03:15,133 --> 00:03:16,683
Let him have it.

59
00:03:17,961 --> 00:03:19,499
And that fake smile.

60
00:03:20,217 --> 00:03:22,154
You've been looking forward
to the beach.

61
00:03:22,624 --> 00:03:23,566
Let her cook.

62
00:03:23,718 --> 00:03:25,730
Let your father put some stones
by that wall

63
00:03:25,871 --> 00:03:28,419
so we stop getting water
underneath the deck.

64
00:03:28,706 --> 00:03:32,252
I guess I won't have to worry about
talking to her. She never stops.

65
00:03:33,084 --> 00:03:34,877
Just get through today.

66
00:03:35,279 --> 00:03:37,227
I'll be there tomorrow afternoon.

67
00:03:37,641 --> 00:03:39,532
We'll go to that place
with the lobster rolls.

68
00:03:39,783 --> 00:03:40,999
Just come now.

69
00:03:42,030 --> 00:03:43,702
You hate the way I drive.

70
00:03:44,405 --> 00:03:45,970
Well, my father taught me.

71
00:03:46,719 --> 00:03:48,491
Half the office has cleared out.

72
00:03:55,561 --> 00:03:57,399
<i>kennedy, kennedy, kennedy, kennedy,</i>

73
00:04:00,363 --> 00:04:02,758
<i>Do you like a man who
answers straight?</i>

74
00:04:02,919 --> 00:04:04,739
<i>A man who's always fair?</i>

75
00:04:04,907 --> 00:04:06,907
<i>we'll measure him against the others</i>

76
00:04:07,115 --> 00:04:08,865
<i>and when you compare.</i>

77
00:04:09,649 --> 00:04:11,129
Looks like a maple ad.

78
00:04:11,319 --> 00:04:12,611
It's incredible.

79
00:04:12,967 --> 00:04:14,449
Happy days are here again.

80
00:04:14,725 --> 00:04:16,428
I'm just wild about Harry.

81
00:04:16,803 --> 00:04:18,752
It's light. It's fun.

82
00:04:19,339 --> 00:04:20,850
Doesn't cloud the mind with,

83
00:04:21,727 --> 00:04:22,966
I don't know, issues.

84
00:04:23,313 --> 00:04:24,424
It's catchy.

85
00:04:24,591 --> 00:04:25,917
Catchy like it gets in your head

86
00:04:26,057 --> 00:04:27,854
and makes you want to blow
your brains out.

87
00:04:31,301 --> 00:04:33,685
The president is a product.
Don't forget that.

88
00:04:37,821 --> 00:04:41,059
<i>I would like to talk to you for
a moment about dollars and cents.</i>

89
00:04:41,510 --> 00:04:43,124
<i>Your dollars and cents.</i>

90
00:04:43,484 --> 00:04:46,198
<i>Now, my opponents want to
increase federal expenditures</i>

91
00:04:46,458 --> 00:04:48,700
<i>as much as $18 billion a year.</i>

92
00:04:49,632 --> 00:04:51,328
<i>How will they pay for it?</i>

93
00:04:51,820 --> 00:04:53,152
<i>There are only two ways.</i>

94
00:04:53,384 --> 00:04:54,873
<i>One is to raise your taxes.</i>

95
00:04:55,384 --> 00:04:56,291
Turn it off.

96
00:04:56,556 --> 00:04:57,572
<i>The other--</i>

97
00:05:00,209 --> 00:05:02,640
An ad made by a public
relations team.

98
00:05:03,883 --> 00:05:05,801
Message received and forgotten.

99
00:05:06,384 --> 00:05:09,028
We should give this
to Franz for some music.

100
00:05:09,760 --> 00:05:12,314
Nixon's campaign song
in the key of E.

101
00:05:12,946 --> 00:05:15,561
Ethal, go get the ice pick

102
00:05:17,062 --> 00:05:19,857
that nixon guy is on tv again.

103
00:05:20,633 --> 00:05:22,234
Should've never been this close.

104
00:05:24,507 --> 00:05:27,443
I'd say we could run them again, but
I don't think you want to see them.

105
00:05:27,568 --> 00:05:29,012
I've seen them, which reminds me,

106
00:05:29,153 --> 00:05:31,219
you people aren't watching
enough television.

107
00:05:31,447 --> 00:05:33,996
It is your job.
The shows and the ads.

108
00:05:34,385 --> 00:05:36,787
I was just wondering, there must
be any number of people

109
00:05:36,963 --> 00:05:38,834
harvesting mud on
Johnny kennedy right now.

110
00:05:39,094 --> 00:05:40,168
Have we heard anything?

111
00:05:40,333 --> 00:05:43,421
We hear things. Nothing useful. He's a
womanizer. That's not gonna hurt him.

112
00:05:44,331 --> 00:05:46,579
Women find out about that
it'll push him up to the top.

113
00:05:46,685 --> 00:05:48,342
Nixon is still ahead in the polls.

114
00:05:48,770 --> 00:05:50,150
Should've never been this close.

115
00:05:51,725 --> 00:05:54,673
Why do we need to attack
when there's a story to tell?

116
00:05:56,774 --> 00:05:58,770
Kennedy, <i>nouveau riche</i>.

117
00:05:59,017 --> 00:06:01,398
Recent immigrant who bought
his way into harvard,

118
00:06:01,658 --> 00:06:03,223
and now he's well bred?

119
00:06:03,687 --> 00:06:04,687
Great.

120
00:06:05,012 --> 00:06:06,891
Nixon is from nothing.

121
00:06:07,507 --> 00:06:10,437
Self-made man.
The abe lincoln of California

122
00:06:10,625 --> 00:06:12,398
who was vice President
of the United States

123
00:06:12,551 --> 00:06:14,657
six years after getting out
of the Navy.

124
00:06:15,236 --> 00:06:17,502
Kennedy, I see a silver spoon.
Nixon,

125
00:06:18,935 --> 00:06:20,273
I see myself.

126
00:06:21,022 --> 00:06:24,098
If we were to run a critical ad,
there are obvious benefits.

127
00:06:24,401 --> 00:06:25,769
When you run an ad that's positive

128
00:06:25,871 --> 00:06:27,544
you're only convincing the people
who are already voting for you,

129
00:06:27,647 --> 00:06:28,787
but when you run an ad that's critical

130
00:06:28,889 --> 00:06:30,638
you get a shot at the people
on the fence.

131
00:06:30,732 --> 00:06:32,346
There are a lot of people
on the fence.

132
00:06:33,189 --> 00:06:35,474
Gentlemen, whether the nixon
campaign wants it or not,

133
00:06:35,734 --> 00:06:38,894
we have to produce a spot that aims
a howitzer at kennedy's balls.

134
00:06:40,126 --> 00:06:41,670
I want to hear ideas...

135
00:06:42,486 --> 00:06:43,649
after the long weekend.

136
00:06:44,228 --> 00:06:46,482
I agree. Let's go down swinging.

137
00:06:49,524 --> 00:06:51,814
If we can switch to a conversation
about paying clients,

138
00:06:51,962 --> 00:06:55,369
Mencken's is coming in today to sign off
on the roll out, father and daughter.

139
00:06:56,311 --> 00:06:59,368
I get the feeling old Abe Schminken
can kill this whole thing.

140
00:07:00,528 --> 00:07:03,288
Of course, the checks have
cleared already but-

141
00:07:03,887 --> 00:07:06,487
Don, I want you to go in and
ride bareback over Paul here.

142
00:07:06,731 --> 00:07:07,548
Done.

143
00:07:11,160 --> 00:07:14,506
And, Don, I want you
on your best behavior.

144
00:07:15,019 --> 00:07:17,497
- Excuse me?
- I know she bothers you.

145
00:07:31,407 --> 00:07:33,222
Miss Holloway, may I?

146
00:07:37,828 --> 00:07:40,517
I really need to get to
the bottom of that.

147
00:07:42,473 --> 00:07:45,048
Yes, I would like to get
a look at those.

148
00:07:53,286 --> 00:07:55,637
Margaret and Mona are off
to block island for labor day.

149
00:07:55,775 --> 00:07:58,652
Gone for the weekend along
with every other wife in town.

150
00:07:58,799 --> 00:08:01,594
We can go anywhere tonight.
We can see a Broadway show

151
00:08:01,882 --> 00:08:05,105
and sit at any table at the colony
with our clothes off if we want to.

152
00:08:05,949 --> 00:08:07,240
How about a movie?

153
00:08:07,760 --> 00:08:09,086
Have you seen <i>The Apartment</i>*?

154
00:08:09,295 --> 00:08:11,236
I went last week with
Mona and Margaret.

155
00:08:11,496 --> 00:08:13,287
I hear Shirley MacLaine is good.

156
00:08:13,439 --> 00:08:14,239
Please.

157
00:08:14,431 --> 00:08:16,133
A white elevator operator,

158
00:08:16,474 --> 00:08:18,660
and a girl at that?
I want to work at that place.

159
00:08:19,699 --> 00:08:21,038
I bet you do.

160
00:08:21,273 --> 00:08:22,965
The way those men treated
that poor girl,

161
00:08:23,175 --> 00:08:25,042
handing her around like
a tray of canapes.

162
00:08:25,303 --> 00:08:26,752
She tried to commit suicide.

163
00:08:27,842 --> 00:08:29,421
So you saw it, huh?

164
00:08:30,966 --> 00:08:32,892
Red, that's not how it is.

165
00:08:33,393 --> 00:08:36,064
Look, it was crude. That's
the way pictures are now.

166
00:08:36,277 --> 00:08:38,538
Did you see that ridiculous <i>Psycho</i>*?

167
00:08:38,771 --> 00:08:40,933
Hollywood isn't happy unless
things are extreme.

168
00:08:41,342 --> 00:08:43,065
It didn't seem that extreme to me.

169
00:08:43,250 --> 00:08:45,587
Are we actually gonna get
in a fight over a movie?

170
00:08:45,779 --> 00:08:48,820
You know, Mona had a dream once
where I hit the dog with a car.

171
00:08:49,178 --> 00:08:50,833
She was mad at me all day,

172
00:08:51,069 --> 00:08:53,476
and I never hit the dog.
We don't even have a dog.

173
00:08:56,852 --> 00:08:58,325
Why don't I call you later?

174
00:09:00,652 --> 00:09:02,538
Call me soon because
we can go anywhere.

175
00:09:03,400 --> 00:09:06,147
The new atrium will make the store
brighter and more vibrant.

176
00:09:06,357 --> 00:09:10,302
The aisles will be wider, spotlighting
these new chrome display cases.

177
00:09:10,620 --> 00:09:12,476
Over here will be a new restaurant.

178
00:09:12,653 --> 00:09:13,764
Elegant tea room.

179
00:09:14,006 --> 00:09:16,472
Modern classic signs and
champagne linens.

180
00:09:16,910 --> 00:09:18,507
A tea room, nice,

181
00:09:19,510 --> 00:09:21,306
but 30% of my ground floor

182
00:09:21,595 --> 00:09:23,779
is devoted to the restaurant business?

183
00:09:24,031 --> 00:09:26,228
Lunch and shopping,
a day of indulgence.

184
00:09:26,488 --> 00:09:27,730
That's what ladies like.

185
00:09:27,990 --> 00:09:30,336
Yes, I saw that in the chapter here.

186
00:09:30,844 --> 00:09:33,207
It's much longer than
the little schedule.

187
00:09:33,365 --> 00:09:35,678
It says we have to close our doors

188
00:09:35,841 --> 00:09:37,448
while it's getting nailed together.

189
00:09:38,539 --> 00:09:39,716
Three months of construction

190
00:09:39,868 --> 00:09:43,704
during which time we build
enormous anticipation.

191
00:09:44,109 --> 00:09:45,551
It's like a movie premiere.

192
00:09:45,841 --> 00:09:47,238
The new Mencken's.

193
00:09:47,633 --> 00:09:49,543
You will have a line the first day.

194
00:09:49,993 --> 00:09:52,435
Even if you have to pay
people to stand in it.

195
00:09:52,613 --> 00:09:53,714
We'll do whatever it takes.

196
00:09:54,413 --> 00:09:55,424
Mr. Draper,

197
00:09:55,820 --> 00:09:58,016
my daughter's presence here
should let you know

198
00:09:58,192 --> 00:09:59,906
that I am not against change,

199
00:10:00,059 --> 00:10:01,889
and let us assume that this is

200
00:10:02,149 --> 00:10:05,809
the most amazing idea in retail
since "Buy one, get one free."

201
00:10:07,130 --> 00:10:08,228
I still don't understand

202
00:10:08,488 --> 00:10:11,992
why we have to throw out
the baby with the water.

203
00:10:12,230 --> 00:10:15,060
Can't I keep what I have
and just build on it?

204
00:10:16,473 --> 00:10:19,021
Honestly, the unpleasant truth...

205
00:10:19,862 --> 00:10:21,741
Is you don't have anything.

206
00:10:22,851 --> 00:10:25,746
Your customers cannot
be depended on anymore.

207
00:10:26,621 --> 00:10:27,666
Their lives have changed.

208
00:10:28,006 --> 00:10:29,696
They're prosperous.

209
00:10:30,272 --> 00:10:33,055
Over the years they've
developed new tastes.

210
00:10:35,337 --> 00:10:36,465
They're like your daughter.

211
00:10:37,975 --> 00:10:39,999
Educated, sophisticated.

212
00:10:41,101 --> 00:10:43,479
They know full well
what they deserve

213
00:10:44,197 --> 00:10:45,958
and they're willing to pay for it.

214
00:10:46,153 --> 00:10:48,454
Why would I want to own a store

215
00:10:48,654 --> 00:10:50,187
that I wouldn't want to shop in?

216
00:10:50,447 --> 00:10:52,281
Mr. Mencken, I don't know
if that's true.

217
00:10:53,349 --> 00:10:55,791
You had no problem
abandoning that second

218
00:10:55,944 --> 00:10:58,612
floor hosiery store on 7th avenue
for your present location,

219
00:10:59,273 --> 00:11:01,907
and that's a story you'll be proud
to tell your grandchildren.

220
00:11:02,167 --> 00:11:04,245
The only problem is they won't care.

221
00:11:05,100 --> 00:11:08,343
As much as grandpa likes
that marble palace,

222
00:11:09,165 --> 00:11:10,749
I can promise you they won't.

223
00:11:11,476 --> 00:11:13,219
They'll look at it and they'll say,

224
00:11:13,470 --> 00:11:16,171
"Grandpa, it must've been hard
back in the olden days."

225
00:11:18,557 --> 00:11:19,754
And it was.

226
00:11:20,477 --> 00:11:22,094
Everybody's jumping to forget it.

227
00:11:22,538 --> 00:11:23,538
Excuse me.

228
00:11:23,913 --> 00:11:27,260
This is not some phony
story you people print

229
00:11:27,413 --> 00:11:28,913
in your fourth of july circulars.

230
00:11:29,067 --> 00:11:31,615
My father actually started
with nothing

231
00:11:32,364 --> 00:11:34,898
and he made it into everything
we're talking about.

232
00:11:35,289 --> 00:11:36,787
Who here can say that?

233
00:11:38,286 --> 00:11:39,862
I meant no disrespect, sir.

234
00:11:40,353 --> 00:11:41,530
None taken.

235
00:11:43,851 --> 00:11:45,242
This is the plan, daddy.

236
00:11:45,724 --> 00:11:47,672
As you can see, it wasn't
just thrown together.

237
00:11:47,836 --> 00:11:50,122
It does seem very well thought out.

238
00:11:50,382 --> 00:11:51,427
It is.

239
00:11:57,055 --> 00:11:58,239
Pleasure to finally meet you.

240
00:11:58,392 --> 00:12:00,858
I hope you two know
what you're doing.

241
00:12:05,472 --> 00:12:08,008
Looks like we both get to keep
our jobs a little while longer.

242
00:12:08,227 --> 00:12:09,391
Don't screw this up.

243
00:12:10,354 --> 00:12:11,641
I think he likes me.

244
00:12:11,914 --> 00:12:15,034
I guarantee you there is nothing
about you he likes.

245
00:12:15,421 --> 00:12:16,602
What about you?

246
00:12:19,850 --> 00:12:21,219
Daddy, can we?

247
00:12:23,612 --> 00:12:26,326
This place reminds of
a czarist ministry.

248
00:12:26,827 --> 00:12:30,173
No matter what the decision,
you don't feel it was yours.

249
00:12:30,414 --> 00:12:33,320
Fortunately, I have no idea
what you're talking about.

250
00:12:34,727 --> 00:12:36,655
He's very good. persuasive.

251
00:12:37,118 --> 00:12:38,163
Yes.

252
00:12:38,652 --> 00:12:41,118
A little dashing for my taste.

253
00:12:51,539 --> 00:12:52,539
Carol,

254
00:12:52,955 --> 00:12:55,127
it's 10:30. Did we have lunch?

255
00:12:55,287 --> 00:12:56,772
'Cause even I can't leave this early.

256
00:12:57,026 --> 00:12:58,646
No- I need to talk to you.

257
00:12:58,978 --> 00:13:00,498
Why aren't you at work?

258
00:13:01,870 --> 00:13:04,481
Don't tell me you're late again.
Do you need to see Dr. Emerson?

259
00:13:05,535 --> 00:13:07,027
- Good grief, Joan.
- Then what?

260
00:13:07,193 --> 00:13:08,867
You walked 12 blocks in a heat wave,

261
00:13:09,008 --> 00:13:11,412
and I see you didn't take my advice
about the dress heels.

262
00:13:13,274 --> 00:13:16,250
You know how mr. Aldridge has
had me reading the slush pile?

263
00:13:16,510 --> 00:13:19,743
Yes, writing the rejection letters.
You told me. It's depressing.

264
00:13:20,374 --> 00:13:22,088
I'm so stupid!

265
00:13:25,321 --> 00:13:27,235
This morning in
the submissions meeting,

266
00:13:27,416 --> 00:13:29,889
the editorial director asked
why we haven't responded

267
00:13:30,076 --> 00:13:32,224
to this poet from Yale, Marlin Rice.

268
00:13:32,605 --> 00:13:35,205
Mr. Aldridge tells him
we never saw it.

269
00:13:35,667 --> 00:13:37,314
Then the director asks me,

270
00:13:37,541 --> 00:13:39,339
and I cover for mr. Aldridge.

271
00:13:40,090 --> 00:13:43,068
I said that I had read it
and rejected it.

272
00:13:43,657 --> 00:13:46,196
Then they made mr. Aldridge fire me.

273
00:13:46,603 --> 00:13:47,740
Honey, that's awful.

274
00:13:48,227 --> 00:13:49,545
He was really sorry about it.

275
00:13:49,793 --> 00:13:52,202
- Of course, that S.O.B. .
- I know.

276
00:13:52,918 --> 00:13:55,795
I'm going to have to ask
my dad for money again.

277
00:13:55,932 --> 00:13:56,832
It's humiliating.

278
00:13:57,315 --> 00:13:59,195
Stop it.
You shouldn't be embarrassed.

279
00:13:59,395 --> 00:14:00,753
There's never enough money.

280
00:14:01,013 --> 00:14:02,809
You always seem to manage.

281
00:14:03,561 --> 00:14:04,465
These men...

282
00:14:05,292 --> 00:14:07,902
Constantly building them up,
and for what?

283
00:14:08,172 --> 00:14:10,220
Dinner. Jewelry. Who cares?

284
00:14:11,583 --> 00:14:13,755
We need to go out and shake
all this loneliness.

285
00:14:13,980 --> 00:14:17,144
All I want to do is sit
in the movies and cry.

286
00:14:17,417 --> 00:14:18,610
No movies.

287
00:14:18,918 --> 00:14:21,065
Let's look for some
actual bachelors.

288
00:14:21,415 --> 00:14:22,561
Empty their wallets.

289
00:14:23,356 --> 00:14:25,989
- I hate Manhattan sometimes.
- Don't say that.

290
00:14:26,256 --> 00:14:27,935
This city's everything.

291
00:14:33,229 --> 00:14:34,761
Where's howdy dowdy at?

292
00:14:35,603 --> 00:14:36,702
What can I do for ya?

293
00:14:36,916 --> 00:14:39,333
I just got off the phone with
Brett Rowley at <i>Dr. Scholl's</i>.

294
00:14:39,734 --> 00:14:43,245
Don't tell me they're coming in again
about the exercise sandals.

295
00:14:43,477 --> 00:14:44,801
Did you tell 'em summer's over?

296
00:14:45,012 --> 00:14:46,832
They're not coming in... ever.

297
00:14:47,260 --> 00:14:49,092
- They're going to the <i>Leo Burnett</i>.
- What?

298
00:14:49,223 --> 00:14:50,242
Why didn't he call me?

299
00:14:50,917 --> 00:14:53,324
Probably because they were
disappointed with the creative.

300
00:14:53,477 --> 00:14:54,991
Rowley called it dull and humorless.

301
00:14:55,602 --> 00:14:57,476
- And what did you say?
- What could I say?

302
00:14:57,736 --> 00:14:59,150
I've never lost an account before,

303
00:14:59,291 --> 00:15:01,240
especially one that was here
before I got here.

304
00:15:01,417 --> 00:15:02,731
So you really put up a fight?

305
00:15:03,294 --> 00:15:05,116
He had very strong feelings.

306
00:15:05,606 --> 00:15:07,069
He said some unpleasant things.

307
00:15:07,541 --> 00:15:09,988
Which you don't remember
or I'm sure you'd tell me.

308
00:15:14,541 --> 00:15:17,971
The day you sign a client is
the day you start losing them.

309
00:15:21,964 --> 00:15:23,964
Are you going to tell Sterling,
or should I?

310
00:15:24,138 --> 00:15:26,333
Unless you think it can wait
until after the weekend?

311
00:15:26,585 --> 00:15:28,048
I'll take care of it.

312
00:15:41,209 --> 00:15:44,215
Were you buzzing me? My intercom
was making a funny sound.

313
00:15:47,911 --> 00:15:48,891
Leave it.

314
00:15:50,629 --> 00:15:52,156
You wear <i>Dr. Scholl's</i> inserts?

315
00:15:52,583 --> 00:15:53,558
I thought we all had to.

316
00:15:53,828 --> 00:15:54,990
Take them out.

317
00:15:56,829 --> 00:15:57,870
Get rid of this, please.

318
00:16:09,048 --> 00:16:10,445
We lost <i>Dr. Scholl's</i>.

319
00:16:11,308 --> 00:16:12,313
Where?

320
00:16:13,434 --> 00:16:14,434
<i>Leo Burnett</i>.

321
00:16:14,641 --> 00:16:18,152
Campbell enjoyed telling me it was
something to do with creative.

322
00:16:18,856 --> 00:16:21,552
Thought I should tell you. Make
sure the ink is dry on that raise.

323
00:16:21,739 --> 00:16:23,266
That fat piece of shit.

324
00:16:24,150 --> 00:16:25,397
He's a cigarette ash.

325
00:16:26,122 --> 00:16:27,949
Chicago, what a joke.

326
00:16:28,185 --> 00:16:29,190
Small time.

327
00:16:30,058 --> 00:16:31,866
Sorry, maybe you're from there.

328
00:16:33,182 --> 00:16:35,401
I know I didn't drop
the ball on this.

329
00:16:35,818 --> 00:16:36,825
Sales are steady.

330
00:16:37,215 --> 00:16:38,495
Probably didn't help that

331
00:16:38,671 --> 00:16:40,791
our billings crept up
for no apparent reason.

332
00:16:41,558 --> 00:16:44,538
Eventually, an accountant
is gonna read the mail.

333
00:16:46,051 --> 00:16:47,669
If you're trying to cheer me up,
it's working.

334
00:16:48,470 --> 00:16:50,877
The day you sign a client is
the day you start losing 'em.

335
00:16:51,248 --> 00:16:52,611
You don't really believe that.

336
00:16:52,794 --> 00:16:54,250
You know what my father used to say?

337
00:16:54,462 --> 00:16:56,446
Being with a client is like
being in a marriage.

338
00:16:56,753 --> 00:16:58,686
Sometimes you get into it
for the wrong reasons

339
00:16:58,863 --> 00:17:00,891
and eventually they hit you
in the face.

340
00:17:04,746 --> 00:17:05,746
Damn it.

341
00:17:06,615 --> 00:17:09,666
Are we supposed to cry about this?
So we lost an account.

342
00:17:09,853 --> 00:17:11,473
That means we'll just
have to cut back.

343
00:17:11,661 --> 00:17:12,778
Let's go fire somebody.

344
00:17:15,874 --> 00:17:17,167
Labor day weekend.

345
00:17:18,087 --> 00:17:19,625
Between now and monday

346
00:17:19,823 --> 00:17:22,121
we have to fall in love
a dozen times.

347
00:17:22,998 --> 00:17:25,241
Betty's at the shore.
I'm headed down tomorrow.

348
00:17:25,437 --> 00:17:26,754
What do we work so hard for?

349
00:17:26,933 --> 00:17:28,859
To have enough money
to buy fabulous vacations

350
00:17:29,058 --> 00:17:30,808
for our family so
we can live it up here.

351
00:17:31,007 --> 00:17:33,215
Give me tonight. You owe me that.

352
00:17:33,687 --> 00:17:35,220
I can use you as bait.

353
00:17:36,434 --> 00:17:38,826
There's a casting call at 4:00.

354
00:17:39,216 --> 00:17:40,989
Double-sided aluminum.

355
00:17:41,558 --> 00:17:43,090
If Freddy Rumson's brain works

356
00:17:43,243 --> 00:17:45,039
the way I think it works,
slow and obvious,

357
00:17:45,221 --> 00:17:47,913
I think we should go down to casting
and see who's on the couch.

358
00:17:48,099 --> 00:17:50,177
Remember, Don, when
God closes the door

359
00:17:50,452 --> 00:17:51,900
he opens a dress.

360
00:17:58,437 --> 00:18:00,321
What do you have there?
Precious cargo?

361
00:18:00,560 --> 00:18:03,152
Mr. Rumson has me trafficking
the <i>Belle Jolie</i> patch.

362
00:18:03,435 --> 00:18:05,025
Aren't you a busy beaver?

363
00:18:05,575 --> 00:18:07,541
Hey, I'm talking to you.

364
00:18:11,216 --> 00:18:14,093
If you want to see the proofs, you'll
have to check with mr. Cosgrove.

365
00:18:14,241 --> 00:18:15,247
It's his account.

366
00:18:15,439 --> 00:18:17,747
Look at you. Minister of protocol.

367
00:18:18,687 --> 00:18:20,512
So, has Draper talked to
Sterling yet?

368
00:18:20,872 --> 00:18:21,969
You'll have to ask him.

369
00:18:22,188 --> 00:18:23,188
I'm asking you.

370
00:18:23,413 --> 00:18:24,962
You should talk to him.

371
00:18:26,012 --> 00:18:27,045
What's wrong with you?

372
00:18:27,748 --> 00:18:28,748
Excuse me?

373
00:18:29,372 --> 00:18:32,232
I'm just trying to do my job and
you're making it very difficult.

374
00:18:32,936 --> 00:18:35,150
Peggy dear, I think I understand
what this is about,

375
00:18:35,336 --> 00:18:37,826
but you're not being
professional right now.

376
00:18:38,125 --> 00:18:40,324
I cannot believe
I am in this conversation.

377
00:18:40,937 --> 00:18:42,701
Think this is easy for me?

378
00:18:43,628 --> 00:18:44,859
I don't know.

379
00:18:45,800 --> 00:18:49,017
I don't know if you like me
or if you don't like me.

380
00:18:50,185 --> 00:18:52,127
I'm just trying to get along here,

381
00:18:52,500 --> 00:18:54,929
and every time I walk by I wonder

382
00:18:55,971 --> 00:18:57,321
are you going to be nice to me

383
00:18:59,623 --> 00:19:01,595
- or cruel.
- Cruel?

384
00:19:02,626 --> 00:19:05,066
What am I supposed to say?
I'm married.

385
00:19:06,435 --> 00:19:08,645
Yes, I know, and I heard all about how

386
00:19:08,844 --> 00:19:11,230
confusing that can be.

387
00:19:11,605 --> 00:19:13,260
Maybe you need me to lay
on your couch

388
00:19:13,448 --> 00:19:15,109
to clear that up for you again.

389
00:19:17,313 --> 00:19:19,693
That's some imagination you've got.

390
00:19:20,312 --> 00:19:21,932
Good thing you're a writer now.

391
00:19:22,126 --> 00:19:23,704
What do you need me for?

392
00:19:32,775 --> 00:19:33,891
It's incredible.

393
00:19:34,041 --> 00:19:35,825
I mean, we're just hanging out
in the art department

394
00:19:35,954 --> 00:19:37,270
and you two wander in.

395
00:19:37,437 --> 00:19:40,019
- We thought it was casting.
- I wish it was.

396
00:19:40,686 --> 00:19:42,205
I'd definitely pick you two.

397
00:19:42,463 --> 00:19:45,514
You have such an exquisite look,
the bones of your face.

398
00:19:46,185 --> 00:19:48,251
And your sister, my goodness.

399
00:19:48,961 --> 00:19:50,405
You two look very different

400
00:19:50,602 --> 00:19:52,229
when you pay attention.

401
00:19:52,750 --> 00:19:54,446
I have an older brother.

402
00:19:54,735 --> 00:19:56,790
My neighbors growing up had a dairy

403
00:19:57,062 --> 00:19:59,293
and one of the cows gave
birth to two calves

404
00:19:59,502 --> 00:20:01,028
that were attached at the back,

405
00:20:01,278 --> 00:20:03,407
then they cut them apart
but they always

406
00:20:03,667 --> 00:20:05,179
wanted to be together.

407
00:20:05,646 --> 00:20:06,994
Is that what happened to you two?

408
00:20:09,937 --> 00:20:11,790
Do you like ukrainian food?

409
00:20:12,200 --> 00:20:13,751
Let me ask you something, Draper.

410
00:20:14,011 --> 00:20:16,070
Do any of these men have
anything else to do?

411
00:20:16,250 --> 00:20:19,006
I just wanted to make sure
the girls were, you know.

412
00:20:19,775 --> 00:20:20,799
Matching?

413
00:20:21,375 --> 00:20:22,375
Exactly.

414
00:20:29,590 --> 00:20:30,601
Well, there you have it.

415
00:20:31,310 --> 00:20:34,480
Double-sided aluminum as
envisioned by <i>Sterling-Cooper</i>.

416
00:20:41,622 --> 00:20:42,862
Look at you.

417
00:20:43,819 --> 00:20:46,496
- Roger Sterling.
- Eleanor Ames.

418
00:20:49,437 --> 00:20:51,330
What a great God that
made two of you.

419
00:20:53,377 --> 00:20:55,831
What a sweet thing to say.
Mirabelle.

420
00:20:57,312 --> 00:20:58,337
This is Donald Draper.

421
00:20:58,597 --> 00:20:59,983
He's our creative director here.

422
00:21:00,160 --> 00:21:02,003
What a pleasure to meet you.

423
00:21:03,929 --> 00:21:05,468
Well, honestly,

424
00:21:06,677 --> 00:21:08,597
I think we're going to send
everyone else home

425
00:21:09,108 --> 00:21:11,785
and use our authority to say
that you two are

426
00:21:11,996 --> 00:21:14,311
the new faces of Cartwright
double-sided aluminum!

427
00:21:14,571 --> 00:21:15,944
My god. thank you.

428
00:21:16,936 --> 00:21:18,692
I think this calls for a celebration.

429
00:21:18,999 --> 00:21:20,275
Come on upstairs with us.

430
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:22,544
One drink could be fun.

431
00:21:23,206 --> 00:21:24,186
One last question.

432
00:21:24,499 --> 00:21:25,956
How many birthdays have you had?

433
00:21:26,155 --> 00:21:27,165
Twenty.

434
00:21:28,481 --> 00:21:29,702
How about her?

435
00:21:35,052 --> 00:21:36,989
You're coming, aren't you, Don?

436
00:21:49,748 --> 00:21:51,788
Aren't you two a pair of bookends.

437
00:21:52,865 --> 00:21:53,872
What do you say, Draper?

438
00:21:54,027 --> 00:21:56,729
Shall we cast 'em in bronze and
mount them on the credenza?

439
00:21:57,120 --> 00:21:59,857
Oh, my. Everything he says means
something else too.

440
00:22:02,939 --> 00:22:04,097
Did get warm in here.

441
00:22:04,313 --> 00:22:06,405
They shut the air off at five.
<i>Rochester</i>,

442
00:22:06,665 --> 00:22:08,574
get her an extra ice cube
or something.

443
00:22:13,822 --> 00:22:16,111
Mirabelle, what's
your special talent?

444
00:22:16,466 --> 00:22:18,751
Singing? Dancing?

445
00:22:19,312 --> 00:22:20,610
Baton twirling?

446
00:22:20,859 --> 00:22:22,763
I ride, mostly just dressage.

447
00:22:22,925 --> 00:22:25,791
She has a wall full of blue ribbons
back home in Winchester.

448
00:22:26,935 --> 00:22:28,260
I have a few awards myself.

449
00:22:30,311 --> 00:22:32,361
Look at your skin. It's translucent.

450
00:22:34,171 --> 00:22:35,469
It's see through.

451
00:22:36,986 --> 00:22:38,214
Can I touch it?

452
00:22:40,548 --> 00:22:42,081
I don't see why not.

453
00:22:42,300 --> 00:22:44,108
After all, I do work here now.

454
00:22:50,169 --> 00:22:51,362
That tickles.

455
00:22:52,204 --> 00:22:53,966
Soft as a lamb's ear.

456
00:22:55,485 --> 00:22:56,889
You gotta feel this.

457
00:22:57,862 --> 00:22:59,649
I'm talking to you, Eleanor.

458
00:23:09,657 --> 00:23:10,636
Do you love your sister?

459
00:23:11,362 --> 00:23:12,362
Of course.

460
00:23:12,981 --> 00:23:15,557
Why don't you show her how much?
Give her a kiss.

461
00:23:16,075 --> 00:23:17,108
Right now.

462
00:23:22,421 --> 00:23:24,393
Why do people always ask us that?

463
00:23:24,986 --> 00:23:27,258
My God, because it's a beautiful thing.

464
00:23:32,116 --> 00:23:33,409
I should be heading home.

465
00:23:33,854 --> 00:23:35,697
Wonder boy, have a great night.

466
00:23:36,038 --> 00:23:37,979
You know what?
I think we should go, too.

467
00:23:38,237 --> 00:23:39,058
Come on.

468
00:23:39,424 --> 00:23:41,037
Nobody's going anywhere.

469
00:23:42,098 --> 00:23:43,210
Do you want to dance?

470
00:23:43,986 --> 00:23:45,087
That's nice.

471
00:23:45,605 --> 00:23:46,650
Dance for us.

472
00:23:49,236 --> 00:23:50,593
I don't dance.

473
00:23:54,610 --> 00:23:56,268
Sure you do. look at that.

474
00:23:59,403 --> 00:24:01,789
I feel like I'm stuck somewhere
between <i>Doris Day</i>

475
00:24:02,012 --> 00:24:04,278
in <i>Pillow Talk</i>* and <i>Midnight Lace</i>*,

476
00:24:05,045 --> 00:24:07,901
and what I need to be is <i>Kim Novak</i>
in just about anything.

477
00:24:08,455 --> 00:24:10,445
You're prettier than <i>Kim Novak</i>.

478
00:24:10,673 --> 00:24:11,780
What a rut.

479
00:24:12,487 --> 00:24:14,502
1960, I'm so over you.

480
00:24:15,116 --> 00:24:16,118
Zip.

481
00:24:22,228 --> 00:24:23,459
Shalimar?

482
00:24:24,071 --> 00:24:25,234
Too much?

483
00:24:26,427 --> 00:24:28,285
You never say die, do you?

484
00:24:28,612 --> 00:24:29,612
What's the point?

485
00:24:32,650 --> 00:24:35,315
Carol, sweetie, it's not that bad.

486
00:24:36,363 --> 00:24:37,890
Tomorrow's another day.

487
00:24:38,553 --> 00:24:39,553
I know.

488
00:24:39,958 --> 00:24:42,770
- I'm okay actually.
- Good.

489
00:24:43,030 --> 00:24:44,855
No water works. Mascara.

490
00:24:45,361 --> 00:24:47,066
I'm just so happy right now.

491
00:24:47,426 --> 00:24:49,026
Okay, are you on the Gilbey's already?

492
00:24:50,050 --> 00:24:53,569
No. I just love this, you know,
being with you.

493
00:24:54,353 --> 00:24:56,537
We do know how
to have fun, don't we?

494
00:24:58,673 --> 00:24:59,673
Joan...

495
00:25:03,174 --> 00:25:04,296
I love you.

496
00:25:06,250 --> 00:25:07,408
I really do.

497
00:25:07,850 --> 00:25:08,754
You.

498
00:25:13,247 --> 00:25:16,476
That first week in college I saw you
walking on the commons

499
00:25:18,378 --> 00:25:19,650
and I thought,

500
00:25:21,386 --> 00:25:22,630
"Who is she?"

501
00:25:25,313 --> 00:25:28,171
Then college was over
and you came here,

502
00:25:29,297 --> 00:25:30,401
and I followed you.

503
00:25:33,314 --> 00:25:34,780
You need a roommate,

504
00:25:36,329 --> 00:25:37,515
I moved in...

505
00:25:40,690 --> 00:25:42,223
Just to be near you.

506
00:25:44,986 --> 00:25:47,299
I did everything I could
to be near you,

507
00:25:48,011 --> 00:25:49,314
all with the hope

508
00:25:50,382 --> 00:25:51,641
that one day

509
00:25:53,370 --> 00:25:54,802
you would notice me.

510
00:25:59,563 --> 00:26:00,563
Joanie.

511
00:26:04,815 --> 00:26:06,548
Think of me as a boy.

512
00:26:16,563 --> 00:26:18,284
You've had a hard day.

513
00:26:20,504 --> 00:26:23,216
Let's go out and try
to forget about it, okay?

